Indigo Exchange - Indigo is the color between blue and purple The color blue represents both the sky and the sea and is associated with open spaces, freedom, imagination and inspiration In the Bible, indigo is associated with the heavens, representing the divine and the spiritual holiness what you won’t find in the history books is the indigo textile was literally used as currency. In the 1700s the profits from indigo outpaced the profits of sugar and cotton. At the time of the American revolution the dollar had no strength and indigo cakes were used as currency. They was out here trading one piece of indigo cloth in exchange for one human. the expressive lines and patterns of this design are meant to resemble broken chains to represent liberation, freedom and inspiration
